declarations.comments: For a given audio context, use an audio buffer to create a browser audio buffer. This is useful when doing DSP in the browser.  Note that `AudioBuffer` is a purescript type whereas `WebAPI.BrowserAudioBuffer` is an optimized browser-based type. That means that, once you write to `WebAPI.BrowserAudioBuffer`, it is effectively a blob and its contents cannot be retrieved using the Ocarina API.
